  "prompt": "I'm presenting some mobile app designs for a portfolio presentation in an interview. Should I make the designs be the full height of the PowerPoint, or do I need to make room for a title of the screen?",
  "response": "When presenting mobile app designs in a PowerPoint portfolio presentation, it\u2019s important to balance showcasing the designs with providing context for the interviewer. Here\u2019s how you can approach it:\n\n1. **Leave Space for a Title**: Dedicate a small section at the top or bottom of the slide for a title or description. This helps the interviewer understand what they\u2019re looking at (e.g., \u201cHome Screen Design\u201d or \u201cUser Flow for Onboarding\u201d). Titles provide clarity and structure to your presentation.\n\n2. **Prioritize the Design\u2019s Visibility**: Make the mobile app design the focal point of the slide. While it doesn\u2019t need to be the **full height** of the slide, it should be large enough for the details to be clearly visible. Avoid squeezing the design too much just to fit a title.\n\n3. **Consider a Clean Layout**:  \n   - Place the title at the top of the slide and center the design below it.  \n   - Alternatively, place the title at the bottom, leaving the design to occupy most of the slide.  \n   - Use a simple, professional font for the title that doesn\u2019t distract from the design.\n\n4. **Use Mockups or Frames**: If you want the design to feel more polished, display it within a mobile device mockup. This can help it stand out while still leaving room for a title or brief description.\n\n5. **Keep It Minimal**: Avoid cluttering the slide with too much text or unnecessary elements. The focus should be on your design, with the title serving as a quick reference.\n\nBy leaving a small area for a title and ensuring the design is clearly visible, you\u2019ll create a professional and polished slide that communicates effectively. Good luck with your presentation!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
